---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---
<BaseLayout title="Projects | SS Developers Case Studies" description="Two software case studies showing how SS Developers handles architecture, trust, operator clarity, and dependable system behaviour.">
  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="page-intro">Case studies</div>
        <h1 class="page-title">Projects that prove how I engineer.</h1>
        <p class="page-copy">
          These are not gallery pieces. They are projects where architecture, data flow, and trust matter more than cosmetic novelty. I show the topology and the tradeoffs without exposing sensitive business logic.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container project-list">
      <article class="project-entry" id="superfib">
        <div class="project-entry-header">
          <div class="stack-lg">
            <div class="eyeline">Trading infrastructure</div>
            <h2 class="project-name">SMC SuperFIB</h2>
            <p class="panel-copy">
              A cross-runtime execution and monitoring system that keeps indicator logic, API state, trading clients, and dashboard visibility aligned.
            </p>
            <p class="project-challenge">The hard part was keeping multiple runtimes in agreement without the operator needing to read raw logs to understand what was happening.</p>
            <a href="/projects/superfib" class="link-inline">Read the full SuperFIB case study</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="detail-layout project-architecture">
          <div class="diagram-panel">
            <div class="diagram-frame">
              <img src="/images/diagram-system/superfib-diagram.png" alt="SuperFIB systems dashboard showing Pine Script status, the WordPress API source of truth, MT5 execution status, and operator visibility." />
            </div>
            <p class="diagram-caption">The architecture keeps the API authoritative while the execution and dashboard layers stay readable for operators.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="stack-lg">
            <div class="panel-title">Architecture</div>
            <p class="section-copy">
              The API is the authority. The indicator, execution layer, and dashboard all reconcile against it so parity can be checked and stale state can be caught early.
            </p>
            <p class="section-copy">
              The value here is not the number of moving parts. It is that each part has a clear role and the operator can see what the system believes without guessing.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="project-entry" id="stokvel">
        <div class="project-entry-header">
          <div class="stack-lg">
            <div class="eyeline">Community finance</div>
            <h2 class="project-name">Stokvel Society</h2>
            <p class="panel-copy">
              A fintech platform for contribution tracking, ledger visibility, and payout flows designed around clarity for members and administrators.
            </p>
            <p class="project-challenge">The hard part was turning a trust-heavy community finance workflow into software that feels calm, clear, and dependable.</p>
            <a href="/projects/stokvel" class="link-inline">Read the full Stokvel Society case study</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="detail-layout project-architecture">
          <div class="diagram-panel">
            <div class="diagram-frame">
              <img src="/images/diagram-system/stokvel-society-dashboard.png" alt="Stokvel Society wallet dashboard showing member contributions, ledger trust checks, and payout status." />
            </div>
            <p class="diagram-caption">The product focuses on keeping money movement understandable, auditable, and easy to verify.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="stack-lg">
            <div class="panel-title">Architecture</div>
            <p class="section-copy">
              This flow is intentionally simpler. Contributions move into a ledger layer that acts as the financial core, and the payout path stays understandable to the people relying on it.
            </p>
            <p class="section-copy">
              The architecture matters because clarity is part of the product. People need to understand where the money is, what changed, and what happens next.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
